    {
        "content": "<p>If A&gt;=B and c&lt;0 then it's not true that <code>c*A &gt;= c*B</code>, the inequality gets switched, that looks like the problem to me (i.e. you're making a mathematical error, not a Lean error). Similarly A&gt;=-2 and B&gt;=2 doesn't imply AB&gt;=-4 (e.g. A could be -1 and B could be 100000000000000000000)</p>",
        "id": 449417374,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1720225244
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks for spotting that mathematical error! </p>\n<p>The suggests I need to go back to the drawing board on what a \"plain English\" proof would look like before attempting to do a Lean proof.</p>\n<p>As an aside, am I right to think that the <code>rel</code> tactic can reason about linear expressions, like A and B, but not higher order expressions like AB, again from your example? Alternatively, perhaps the <code>rel</code> tactic can reason about monotonically increasing/decreasing expressions like A=x^3 but not A=x^2 (over ℝ)?</p>\n<p>The only docs I could find are at <a href=\"https://github.com/haruhisa-enomoto/mathlib4-all-tactics/blob/main/all-tactics.md#rel\">https://github.com/haruhisa-enomoto/mathlib4-all-tactics/blob/main/all-tactics.md#rel</a> which don't seem helpful to beginners like me.</p>",
        "id": 449420555,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1720228182
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>rel</code> attempts to use <code>gcongr</code>, it attempts to recursively compare the terms, and adds the required assumptions as goals (I think in <code>rel</code> it only uses the list you give)</p>",
        "id": 449478856,
        "sender_full_name": "Daniel Weber",
        "timestamp": 1720264971
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"690858\">@Daniel Weber</span>  - so if we asked <code>rel</code> or <code>gcongr</code> to reason about a mapping <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">9(x-1)(x-2)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">9</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> which is not monotonic then it looks at the terms (in the expanded polynomial) and identifies some that \"go up\" and \"some that go down\" and concludes that it can't reason about an inequality. Is that correct about how it works?</p>",
        "id": 449479398,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1720265452
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No, it identifies only the ones that go up</p>",
        "id": 449479634,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1720265527
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As far as I understand, it tries to write it as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> 9 (y-1) (x - 2)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">9</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, then recursively compares — the outermost operator is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mn>9</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>∗</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> (9 (x-1)) * (x - 2)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord\">9</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">))</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, then it sees that the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> x-2 </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span> is equal, and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>≤</mo><mn>9</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> 9 (x-1) ≤ 9 (y-1)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">9</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">9</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, so it concludes that it needs the assumption <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> 0 ≤ x-2 </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7804em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span></span></span></span></p>",
